    "paragraphs": [
      {
        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "SRD‑46 shows several **very strong Pb²⁺ ligands**, but the database coverage for classic clinical lead chelators is incomplete. Among the **Pb²⁺ systems actually present**, the strongest binders are mostly **synthetic polyaminocarboxylates and macrocycles**, not the standard bedside agents.\n\n| Rank basis in SRD‑46 | Ligand in database | Ligand ID | Conditions represented | Clinical use for lead poisoning? |\n|---|---|---:|---|---|\n| Very high affinity class | trans‑1,2‑Cyclohexylenedinitrilotetraacetic acid (CDTA) | ligand_6301 | 25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | No standard clinical use |\n| Very high affinity class | Diethylenetrinitrilopentaacetic acid (DTPA) | ligand_6356 | 25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | Not standard for lead poisoning |\n| Very high affinity class | Ethylenedinitrilotetraacetic acid (EDTA) | ligand_6277 | 25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | **Yes** — clinically relevant as **CaNa2EDTA** |\n| Very high affinity class | Oxybis(ethylenenitrilo)tetraacetic acid (EGTA-like family member) | ligand_6335 | 20–25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | No standard clinical use |\n| Very high affinity class | Nitrilotriacetic acid / related aminocarboxylates | ligand_6165 and others | mostly 20–25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | No |\n| High affinity but specialized | Large aza macrocycles / cryptand-like ligands | ligand_7532, 7509, 7522, 7540, 7541, etc. | mostly 25 °C, I ≈ 0.1 M | No clinical lead use |\n| Moderate–high thiol binders present | Penicillamine | ligand_5857 | 25 °C, I = 3 M | **Historically/occasionally used**, not first-line now |\n| Moderate–high thiol binders present | Cysteine, mercaptoethanol, related thiols | ligand_5856, 9747, 9748, etc. | variable | No routine clinical use |",
